"Schwann cells","Sustentacular cells","Basal cells","Goblet cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory epithelium contains several distinct cell types. \u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cells\u003C/strong\u003E function as stem cells that continuously generate new olfactory receptor neurons throughout life, making the olfactory epithelium one of few sites of adult neurogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESustentacular cells\u003C/strong\u003E provide metabolic and structural support to olfactory receptor neurons but do not generate new neurons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrush cells\u003C/strong\u003E are rare chemosensory cells found in respiratory epithelium but not in olfactory epithelium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoblet cells\u003C/strong\u003E are mucus-secreting cells found in respiratory epithelium but not in olfactory epithelium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchwann cells\u003C/strong\u003E support peripheral nerves but are not found within the olfactory epithelium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory epithelium develops embryologically from specialised ectoderm called the olfactory placode. The presence of stem cells in this tissue allows for ongoing replacement of damaged olfactory receptor neurons throughout life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The olfactory epithelium develops from ectoderm of the olfactory placode.","Olfactory receptor neurons differentiate from basal cells in the olfactory epithelium throughout life.","The olfactory epithelium is one of few sites where adult neurogenesis occurs."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevis